  "prompt": "What are the penalties for money laundering under federal law?",
  "response": "Under federal law in the United States, money laundering is a serious crime with severe penalties. The specific penalties for money laundering are outlined in the **Bank Secrecy Act (BSA)** and the **Money Laundering Control Act of 1986** (18 U.S.C. \u00a7\u00a7 1956 and 1957). Here are the key penalties:\n\n1. **Criminal Penalties:**\n   - **Imprisonment:** Individuals convicted of money laundering can face up to **20 years in federal prison** per violation. \n   - **Fines:** The maximum fine for a money laundering conviction is **$500,000 or twice the value of the property involved in the transaction, whichever is greater.**\n   - In cases involving violations of the **BSA**, such as failing to report transactions or structuring transactions to avoid reporting, penalties can include **up to 10 years in prison** and **fines up to $500,000.**\n\n2. **Civil Penalties:**\n   - Civil forfeiture of property involved in or traceable to money laundering activities is common. This means the government can seize assets believed to be connected to the crime.\n   - Financial penalties for violations can range from **$10,000 to $100,000 per violation**, depending on the severity and nature of the offense.\n\n3. **Enhanced Penalties for Certain Circumstances:**\n   - If the money laundering involves proceeds from specified unlawful activities (e.g., drug trafficking, terrorism, or organized crime), penalties can be even more severe.\n   - Transactions exceeding **$10,000** in value can trigger additional scrutiny and harsher penalties.\n\n4. **Corporate Liability:**\n   - Businesses or financial institutions involved in money laundering can face significant fines, loss of licenses, and reputational damage. The **USA PATRIOT Act** also imposes strict anti-money laundering (AML) compliance requirements on financial institutions.\n\nThese penalties are designed to deter money laundering and punish those who attempt to conceal the proceeds of illegal activities. Prosecutors often pursue charges aggressively, especially in cases involving large sums of money or connections to serious crimes.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
